In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April 2009 as National Child Abuse Prevention Month. He emphasizes the importance of understanding child abuse and the need for all Americans to help families overcome this issue. The article highlights that child abuse can occur physically, sexually, emotionally, and through neglect. It stresses that well-informed and strong families are the best defense against child abuse. The article encourages community members to offer their time and support to parents and children in need, either through organized parent support groups or by simply lending a helping hand. It also emphasizes the role of civic organizations and government in providing education, assistance, treatment, funding for services, and enforcement of child abuse laws. The proclamation concludes by urging all citizens to contribute to the physical, emotional, and developmental needs of children to prevent and respond to child abuse.